  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1408735063" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1408735063" />
    <a title="Jaycob Izso" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30522283-jaycob-izso"><img alt="Jaycob Izso" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1397432011p2/30522283.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1408735063?book_show_action=true">Oct 04, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jaycob Izso" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jaycob Izso" href="/user/show/30522283-jaycob-izso">Jaycob Izso</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780415277013" href="/book/show/770903.History_of_Madness">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1408735063" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10096146167325624258">There are very few academic texts written in the past 50-60 years which deserve the coveted status that we have granted to Marx&apos;s Capital or Hegel&apos;s Phenomenology of Spirit; that is to say, the status of being historically revolutionary and brilliant within the confines of a given field. Blasphemous though it might seem: this text should be counted as one of them. As many other reviewers have stated - it is a long book; the single longest text Foucault ever produced. But despite the popularity a</span>
  <span id="freeText10096146167325624258" style="display:none">There are very few academic texts written in the past 50-60 years which deserve the coveted status that we have granted to Marx's Capital or Hegel's Phenomenology of Spirit; that is to say, the status of being historically revolutionary and brilliant within the confines of a given field. Blasphemous though it might seem: this text should be counted as one of them. As many other reviewers have stated - it is a long book; the single longest text Foucault ever produced. But despite the popularity and relative ease of History of Sexuality, it is this book that should be considered Foucault's magnum opus.<br /><br /> The charm of the text is not found in its capacious (albeit occasionally bizarre) narrative - Foucault is organized to be sure; yet any artistry in the overall narrative can be lost in the detailed nuance and technical brilliance of each section. The common trend amongst readers of this book is to read the text piecemeal (it's virtually impossible not to if one is reading carefully). Foucault may have grown sensitive to this whilst preparing the book for the multiple years that he did, or maybe his train of thought was literally too detailed in sections for him to maintain a common thread for longer than 10-20 pages. In any event, the result is a text that has a dense amount of information in spurts and is occasionally repetitive in its sub-theses (certainly with respect to whatever passes for an ontological conclusion by Foucault).<br /><br /> The beauty of the structure of History of Madness underscores the closest thing to a methodology we can grasp from any single Foucault piece. Like most of his work, Foucault commits to to a decent amount of discursive hermeneutics and legal exegesis. What becomes clear by the end of Part 1 however, is that this hermetical approach allows Foucault to locate the intersections between areas of discourse generation. He is able to then take these connection points and ask we the reader to turn them around, so as to face the institutions and figures which have propagated and utilized the power of these discourses and the "reasoning" behind them. Still Foucault doesn't stop there; upon finding these complex spaces of discursive interplay Foucault will take us beyond and outside of them. The spaces for interplay become useful to the functioning of power as it is carried out, but the current of power (be it through reason, medicine, or simply knowledges in general) that provides the medium for the discourse generation and its intersections is what ends up being more fascinating for Foucault's analysis. <br /><br /> By the end of Part 2 (and certainly in the Appendices) it is clear where the trajectory of Foucault's work was headed. The idea of a "technology of power" was firmly rooted in the writing of this book. Foucault's intermingling with Deleuze and the notion of a "dispositif" finds its potential for recognition here as well. Even the critical notions of "archaeology" and "genealogy" are explored and carried out throughout the entirety of the text. If one is serious about investigating Foucault on an academic level, this is the text to analyze given its formative qualities in Foucault's writing.<br /><br /> To paraphrase Ian Hacking in the introduction to the newest edition: how can you introduce a masterpiece? How can you prevent a text of this magnitude from speaking for itself? History of Madness certainly does just that. Note takers will find that their notes (be it through Foucault's colorful concepts or his use of references) will total nearly the same amount of pages as the book itself. Again, certain parts of the text are redundant, and represent more an attempt by Foucault to work out his own unique method whilst approaching a variety of different historical works and events. Another area of consideration for the text is the historical criticism Foucault began to receive from American thinkers around 1980-81 (Peter Gay being one significant example). But the whole question as to whether or not there really was a "ship of fools" or not detracts from the philosophical brilliance of the text - if one is looking to this text as a template for rigorously accurate historical work I have a suspect feeling they will be met with disappointment. <br /><br /> As to whether this full version of History of Madness is more valuable than the abridged Madness and Civilization - it depends on the amount of time you wish to spend on a single text and what you are looking to get out of reading Foucault. Part of the appeal of History of Madness is that it is more personal - Foucault backtracks at various times and even openly hesitates on the information he provides. It shows a sort of uncertainty and budding yet oscillating level of confidence from the man so inconically portrayed as stone-faced and stoic with his shaved head and monochromatic sweaters. In the abridged addition readers lose the details of Foucault's curious yet fascinating critique of Descartes, they miss large sections of his exploration of the conditions of the mad both in and out of confinement; most of Part III of History of Madness is missing from Madness and Civilization entirely. To those truly fascinated with Foucault and his thought, reading the entirety of History of Madness is a must. Though if one is looking for the genesis of the American critique of Foucauldian scholarship, it is worth while to look at the structure of Madness and Civilization.<br /><br /> In the end this is simply an amazing, rich, complex, and brilliant text. It requires time and detailed amount of effort, but it provides a critical piece of the puzzle that is so often glossed over or merely forgotten in modern Foucault literature and scholarship. Foucault's intellectual brilliance is astounding, there are various times when I teared-up while reading this at the sheer beauty and mosaic-like artistry that Foucault brings to the vicissitudes of his analysis. For those truly serious about contemporary philosophical thought or simply Foucault - this book is a must.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10096146167325624258" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

